Set an interval before the Promise starts, and clear it once the Promise resolves (or rejects, if you wish):

```
const intervalID = setInterval(() =&gt; {
  console.log(&#39;1 second awaited&#39;);
}, 1000);
try {
  await myFunction();
} catch(e) {
  // ...
}
clearInterval(intervalId);
```

Or, if the `catch` can throw too (which it probably shouldn&#39;t):

```
const intervalID = setInterval(() =&gt; {
  console.log(&#39;1 second awaited&#39;);
}, 1000);
try {
  await myFunction();
} catch(e) {
  // ...
} finally {
  clearInterval(intervalId);
}
```

Might look nicer without `await`:

```
const intervalID = setInterval(() =&gt; {
  console.log(&#39;1 second awaited&#39;);
}, 1000);
myFunction()
  .catch(handleErrors) // either make sure handleErrors doesn&#39;t throw, or catch again
  .then(() =&gt; {
    clearInterval(intervalId);
  });
```
